{
  "analysis": "The debug output shows that dot2 (my current order) = 0x1.0207b8p-3, but dot1 = 0x1.0207b4p-3 which is slightly smaller. The reference binary produces 76, which corresponds to the smaller dot product value. The original computes dot1 order: n.x*ld.x + (n.y*ld.y + n.z*ld.z), which gives 0x1.0207b4p-3, leading to intensity 0x1.34030p-2 and pixel value 76.",
  "plan": "Update the diffuse dot product to use the dot1 order: n.x*ld.x + (n.y*ld.y + n.z*ld.z). Then compile, run, and compare.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "sed -i 's/(n.x*ld.x+n.y*ld.y)+n.z*ld.z/n.x*ld.x+(n.y*ld.y+n.z*ld.z)/' /app/mystery.c && grep -n 'df=' /app/mystery.c\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "gcc -O2 -static -o /app/reversed /app/mystery.c -lm && /app/mystery && cp /app/image.ppm /tmp/ref.ppm && /app/reversed && cp /app/image.ppm /tmp/mine.ppm && perl -e 'sub rp{open(F,$_[0]);<F>;<F>;<F>;my @p;while(<F>){push @p,split;}return @p;} my @r=rp(\"/tmp/ref.ppm\");my @m=rp(\"/tmp/mine.ppm\");my $n=scalar(@r);my $d=0;for my $i(0..$n-1){if($r[$i]!=$m[$i]){$d++;if($d<=10){my $px=$i/3;my $y=int($px/800);my $x=$px%800;print \"idx $i x=$x y=$y ch=\",$i%3,\" ref=$r[$i] mine=$m[$i]\\n\";}}}print \"total=$n diffs=$d\\n\";'\n",
      "duration": 1.0
    }
  ]
}
